summary:
President Trump urged NATO allies and China to send warships to guard oil shipments through the Strait of Hormuz after Iran's closure. This follows his call yesterday for allies to deploy warships. U.S. Energy Secretary Jennifer Granholm warned high oil prices will persist. Global oil shipments face disruptions, with affected countries including major importers in Europe and Asia.

Pakistani airstrikes targeted areas in Afghanistan, killing 75 civilians and displacing 115,000 people. Pakistan and Afghanistan vowed further escalation absent peace talks. In eastern Congo, Rwanda-backed rebels overran Goma after defeating government troops, displacing over 1 million residents now crowding the aid hub. NATO launched its first coordinated response after a second Baltic Sea cable severance, following the initial cut yesterday; the alliance is bolstering defenses for European energy and telecom networks.

Republicans blocked Democrats' calls for public hearings on the U.S.-Iran war, now in its third week, delaying testimony from Trump officials. Israel permitted Palestinians to return to northern Gaza on foot after a hostage deal breakthrough, while Rafah crossing closure halted medical evacuations for thousands of patients. UK Prime Minister Keir Starmer told mostly European leaders in a virtual meeting that Russia must accept Ukraine ceasefire talks amid stalled negotiations. Myanmar's junta convened a proxy parliament in Naypyidaw, its first since the 2021 coup. SpaceX launched Crew-10 from Florida to the International Space Station, set to retrieve U.S. astronauts Butch Wilmore and Suni Williams after nine months and dock Saturday. Severe storms brought snow to the Midwest, high winds to the Plains, and tornado risks to the mid-Atlantic, disrupting travel for millions."}
